(60,'parsifal attribute test',' 921iihj kjhu800 ujkwe6697 iu800 mu800 au800 sdfu800 keu800 au800 meas urement andu800 getu800 au800 ru800 esuu800 ltu800 omega . weu800 nowu800 assume weu800 canu800 talk ofu800 anu800 object with theu800 property omega . weu800 cannota sayu800 that theu800 object isu800 oru800 isu800 inu800 theu800 state omega asu800 this description might notu800 beu800 precise enough inu800 theu800 sense that theu800 object might have additional properties asu800 well theu800 color redu800 isu800 anu800 insufficient characterization ofu800 anu800 object . weu800 have theu800 fantasy that au800 sufficient number ofu800 properties will uniquely describe anu800 object this fantasy might notu800 beu800 true . weu800 used language tou800 assign theu800 property tou800 theu800 object butu800 weu800 should rather have used language which assigns theu800 property tou800 theu800 relation ofu800 both theu800 measurement device andu800 theu800 object. andu800 weu800 should notu800 ignore that inu800 addition tou800 measurement device andu800 object there isu800 also au800 certain rest inu800 theu800 universe. inu800 theu800 endu800 weu800 should talk about theu800 property being connected tou800 theu800 measurement device theu800 object andu800 theu800 rest ofu800 theu800 universe. however itu800 isu800 more convenient atu800 least inu800 theu800 beginning tou800 assume that theu800 property belongs tou800 theu800 object alone andu800 take theu800 journey from there. also lkju800 weu800 must admit that there areu800 observations honu800 mandel dipu800 andu800 theories particle number operator notu800 always precisely defined inu800 fock space which make itu800 difficult tou800 talk about well-defined objects ofu800 which weu800 have theu800 fantasy that they canu800 beu800 identified andu800 even ifu800 they dou800 notu800 carry identity that theu800 atu800 least could beu800 counted inu800 numbers ofu800 au800 kind. weu800 make theu800 observation ifu800 weu800 measure au800 property twice immediately after each other leaving nou800 time foru800 development inu800 between weu800 getu800 theu800 same result. this might notu800 beu800 theu800 case foru800 every measurement there areu800 measuremetns foru800 which this isu800 notu800 true andu800 where weu800 describe theu800 measurement asu800 anu800 interaction which changes theu800 object inu800 au800 wayu800 andu800 there areu800 measurements which cannot beu800 made twice inu800 au800 rowu800 asu800 foru800 example they destroy theu800 measured object byu800 theu800 very actu800 ofu800 observation -- atu800 least that isu800 howu800 weu800 describe theu800 situations inu800 these cases butu800 atu800 least weu800 canu800 assume this foru800 au800 class ofu800 ideal measurements. under this assumption after theu800 measurement weu800 talk about theu800 property ofu800 theu800 object inu800 au800 precise manner inu800 theu800 sense that au800 repeated measurement leads tou800 theu800 same result. sou800 howu800 would weu800 describe theu800 object before theu800 measurement assume weu800 make theu800 observation that anu800 object mayu800 lead tou800 different measurement results. weu800 find when weu800 measure different objects ofu800 au800 certain kind ofu800 which weu800 believe weu800 know nou800 difference short ofu800 knowing somehow that they areu800 different whyu800 would they lead tou800 different measurement results. au800 even worse weu800 assumed that weu800 knew au800 property after theu800 measurement. sou800 weu800 know theu800 object asu800 such. weu800 canu800 describe this asu800 oneu800 property isu800 still missing which weu800 didu800 notu800 measure inu800 that measurement foru800 example weu800 measured color andu800 notu800 smell andu800 ifu800 weu800 hadu800 measured itu800 weu800 would have realized that theu800 object isu800 indeed different. weu800 canu800 describe this asu800 before theu800 measurement theu800 object didu800 notu800 have theu800 property weu800 measured itu800 wasu800 imprinted byu800 theu800 measurement . before theu800 measurement theu800 object hadu800 that property only tou800 au800 certain degree andu800 foru800 some reason theu800 measurement process selected this andu800 notu800 that aspect ofu800 theu800 property. 1u800 5u800 su800 su800 hu800 jku800 jklu800 1u800 asu800 du800 au800 sdu800 asu800 du800 this isu800 juu800 stu800 anu800 example veu800 ryu800 su800 mu800 au800 llu800 ku800 category danteinitialcontents '),
