(66,'== Titel ==\n\n<amsmath n=\"Myname\">aix q kk  1 2 3d ss fghjghj56 876qq kjha slkjh  hallo q1 jk aa s wwad fs d a andsom more  st uff which in side o f this   d\n   \n\\xcx\n\nRule of 14cm  \n\\hrule height 1px depth 1px width 14cm \\relax         \n\nRule  of 14.2cm \n\\hrule height 1px depth 1px width 14.2cm \\relax\n\nRule of s 15cm\n\\hrule height 1px depth 1px width 15cm \\relax\n\nRule of 16cm\n\\hrule height 1px depth 1px width 16cm \\relax\n</amsmath>\n\n== Part 2 ==\n<amsmath>\nb ja q q io qw qw   fje q\n</amsmath>\n\n== One ==\n<beamer b>\nHallo2345123 123 123 \nDas ist jakjh \n$a$=$b$ kjh  kjqh k jkl lkj j h iuhh zh qwe asd u io\n</beamer>\n\n== Stuff ==\n<beamer b>\nThis is no w asdcvb we asd  qwe as d  qwe a sd qw e asd qwe asd qwe asd qwe asd qwe  asd qwe asd qwe asd qwe asd qwe asd beamer a sd\n</beamer>\n\n== Only ==\n\n<amsmath n=\"Myname\">J xust  a test</amsmath>\n\n== Titel Y ==\n\n<amsmath o-proof>\nEa iaaa  sds df ax sd   gg   n s\n</amsmath>\n\n<amsmath c-habanalop>Zwhc \nsdf sdf\nsdfsdf\nxx\nsdfsdf\nas\nsdfsdf\nsdfsdf\n\nsdfsdf\n\nsdfsdf\n\nsdfsdf\n\nsdfsdf\n\nsdfsdf\n\nsdfsdf\n\nsdfsdf\n\nsdfsdf\n\nsdfsdf\n\nsdfsdf\n\nsdfsdfsdf\n\nsdf\n\nsdfe i</amsmath>\n\n<amsmath c=\"Ha bA Na\">\nDrei \\url{https://www.ifi.ch}\n</amsmath>','utf-8'),
(67,'\n\n\nWindow\n* [https://blog.fefe.de \\w]\n* [https://blog.fefe.de Fefe \\w]\n\n\nSide\n* [https://blog.fefe.de \\s]\n* [https://blog.fefe.de Fefe \\s]\n\n\n\'\'\'Example\'\'\'\n* <nowiki>[[Main Page || doub]]</nowiki>\n* [[Main Page || doub]] \n\n* <nowiki>[[Main Page \\| doub]]</nowiki>\n* [[Main Page \\| doub]]\n\n\n\'\'\'Example\'\'\'\n* <nowiki>[[Main Page ┬” style=color:green;]]</nowiki>\n* [[Main Page ┬” style=color:green;]]\n\n\'\'\'Example\'\'\'\n* <nowiki>[[Help:Demo for DanteLinks ┬” style=color:green;]]</nowiki>\n* [[Help:Demo for DanteLinks ┬” style=color:green;]]\n\n\'\'\'Example:\'\'\' Adding style attributes to an external link via broken pipe symbol\n* <nowiki>[https://blog.fefe.de Fefe ┬” style=color:green;]</nowiki> produces\n* [https://blog.fefe.de Fefe ┬” style=color:green;]\n\n\n\'\'\'Example:\'\'\' Adding target attribute _blank to an external link opens it in a new tab\n* <nowiki>[https://blog.fefe.de Fefe ┬” target=_blank ]</nowiki> produces:\n* [https://blog.fefe.de Fefe ┬” target=_blank ]\n\nFor use in sidebars only: There is a special class dexternal which can be used to append an external link symbol to link. In the sidebar links which otherwise are external will not show the symbol external. This is as we need query extensions for a number of links in the sidebar and this needs fullurl as parser and this causes the parser to understand the link as external in every case. Therefore we turned this thingie off in sidebar until we find a smart fix for this.\n\n[[Main Page]]\n\nAnd here [[Main Page]] some text [https://blog.fefe.de Fefe] to see the distances when\nrendering in text.\n\n\n== Requirements ==\n\n* We always want to see where a link goes (internal or external)\n* We always want to know where a link opens (same tab, new tab, new window)\n* We want to allow the user to open the link where he wants to (same tab, new tab, new window)\n* We want to force-open some links in specific modes (same tab, new tab, new window) when the user only clicks normally.\n\n== All Link Types ==\n\n<table>\n<tr><td>Internal</td><td><nowiki>[[Main Page]]</nowiki></td><td>[[Main Page]]</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Piped</td><td><nowiki>[[Main Page|Hauptseite]]</nowiki></td><td>[[Main Page|Hauptseite]]</td></tr>\n\n\n<tr><td>External numbered</td><td><nowiki>[https://blog.fefe.de]</nowiki></td><td>[https://blog.fefe.de]</td></tr>\n<tr><td>External text</td><td><nowiki>[https://blog.fefe.de Fefe]</nowiki></td><td>[https://blog.fefe.de Fefe]</td></tr>\n<tr><td>External bare</td><td><nowiki>https://blog.fefe.de</nowiki></td><td>https://blog.fefe.de</td></tr>\n\n\n</table>\n\n\n[[Main Page]]s\n\n[https://blog.fefe.de Fefe]\n\n\n[[Murundai\\w]]\n\n[https://blog.fefe.de Hurundai\\w]\n\n[[Pipetrick (computing)|Pipetrick]] \n\n\n\n\n[[:Category:Root]]','utf-8'),
(68,'\n__SLIDES__\n\n== one ==\nbla\n<amsmath>\nasdqh\na\n\\ubf{q}w  \\ubf{w}er \\ubf janus\n\n</amsmath>\n\n== Link ==\n<amsmath>\n\\dref{Main Page}  \n\n\\dref{Help: Demo for Parsifal}\n\n\\dref{Help: Demo for DanteLinks}\n\n\\dref{Test/Parsifal Section Heading Style}\n\n\\dref{Test/Parsifal Section Heading Style#h4}\n\n\\url{https://www.clemenscap.de} \n\n\n\n</amsmath>\n\n[[Test/Parsifal Section Heading Style#h4]]\n\n[[Demo f├╝r Parsifal]]','utf-8'),
(69,'<amsmath style=\"border:10px solid green;\">\n921iihj kjh ujkWe6697 i m a sdf  ke a meas urement and  get a r esu lt  $\\omega$. We now assume we can talk of an object with the property $\\omega$. We cannota\nsay that the object is (or is in the state) $\\omega$ as this description might not be precise enough in the sense that the object\nmight have additional properties as well (The color red is an insufficient characterization of an object). We have the fantasy that\na sufficient number of properties will uniquely describe an object (This fantasy might not be true).\nWe used language to assign the property to the object but we should rather have used language which assigns the property to the \nrelation of both, the measurement device and the object. And we should not ignore that, in addition to measurement device and object there is\nalso a certain rest in the universe. In the end, we should talk about the property being connected to the measurement device, the object and the rest of the universe. However, it is more convenient, at least in the beginning, to assume that the property belongs to the object \nalone and take the journey from there. Also,lkj  we must admit that there are observations (Hon Mandel dip) and theories (particle number operator not always\nprecisely defined in Fock space) which make it difficult to talk about well-defined objects, of which we have the fantasy that they can be identified, and even if they do not carry identity that the at least could be counted in numbers of a kind.\n\nWe make the observation: If we measure a property twice immediately after each other leaving no time for development in between,\nwe get the same result. This might not be the case for every measurement (there are measuremetns for which this is not true and where we describe the measurement as an interaction which changes the object in a way and\nthere are measurements which cannot be made twice in a row as, for example, they destroy the measured object by the very act of observation -- at least\nthat is how we describe the situations in these cases), but at least we can assume this for a class of ideal measurements. \n\nUnder this assumption: After the measurement we talk about the property of the object in a precise manner in the sense\nthat a repeated measurement leads to the same result.\n\nSo, how would we describe the object before the measurement?\n\nAssume we make the observation, that an object may lead to different measurement results. \nWe find: When we measure (different) objects of a certain kind of which we believe we know no difference (short of knowing somehow that they are different), why would they lead to different measurement results.\n\na\nEven worse: We assumed that we knew a property after the measurement. So we know the object as such. \n\nWe can describe this as: One property is still missing which we did not measure in that measurement (for example we measured color and not smell) and if we had measured it\nwe would have realized that the object is indeed different.\nWe can describe this as: Before the measurement the object did not have the property we measured (it was imprinted by the measurement).\nBefore the measurement the object had that property only to a certain degree, and for some reason the measurement process selected this and not that aspect of the property. \n</amsmath>\n\n\n<amsmath>\n1 5 s s  h jk jkl\n</amsmath>\n\n\n<amsmath>\n1 as d  a sd as d    this is ju st an example\n</amsmath> \n\n<amsmath>\nVe ry s  m a ll k    \n</amsmath>\n\n[[Category:DanteInitialContents]]','utf-8'),
